Url.Title: About WebHelp 2.0
Url.Abstract: About WebHelp 2.0 HTML5 output (also referred to as "WebHelp 2.0" in Flare) is an online format that is the next generation of WebHelp. It is similar to the regular WebHelp format; however, whereas the original WebHelp format works with HTML4, WebHelp 2.0 supports the HTML5 specification developed by the Web Hypertext Application Technology Working Group (WHATWG—http://whatwg.org) and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C—http://w3.org).

Url.Abstract: About This Guide This guide describes the Ixia implementation of the High Level Tcl Application Programming Interface (HLTAPI). The intended audience consists of test technicians who configure Ixia test equipment and software.

Url.Title: HLTAPI Basics
Url.Abstract: HLTAPI Basics This section is meant for readers who are either new to HLTAPI, or are versed in HLTAPI but new to Ixia products. The purpose of this document is to provide a jump start for understanding the concepts of APIs, getting help from the command manual and sample scripts in the distribution, and writing scripts.

Url.Title: ATS Environment
Url.Abstract: ATS Environment ATS users can start using HLTAPI without installing the software themselves. Under ATS, Ixia client software is installed at one location of a Solaris file server. The software includes IxTclHal, IxTclProtocol, IxTclAccess, and others, as well as HLTAPI. The software is accessed through file mounting points, so that Ixia software appears as local files.

Url.Title: Installing Your Own Copy
Url.Abstract: Installing Your Own Copy Install HLTAPI in your own computer under Windows or Linux OS, or a home folder under Solaris.

Url.Title: Namespaces and Packaging
Url.Abstract: Namespaces_Packaging A namespace is a collection of commands and variables. It encapsulates the commands and variables to ensure they do not interfere with the commands and variables of other namespaces.

Url.Title: Command Format: Option Passing
Url.Abstract: Command Format: Option Passing All the HLTAPI calls use dashed (-) options to pass configuration parameters. Note that the option list can be long. It is possible to put everything on one line when scripting, or you can use multiple lines. In this case, the backslash (\ ) is used at the end of each line (except for the last) to signal line-continuation to Tcl.
